```javascript
function checkForPrime(arr) {
  // Function to check if a number is prime
  function isPrime(n) {
    if (n <= 1) {
      return false; // 0 and 1 are not prime
    }
    if (n === 2) {
      return true; // 2 is the only even prime number
    }
    // check if n is divisible by any integer up to the square root of n
    for (let i = 2, sqrt = Math.sqrt(n); i <= sqrt; i++) {
      if (n % i === 0) {
        return false;
      }
    }
    return true;
  }

  // Loop through array and print prime numbers
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (isPrime(arr[i])) {
      console.log(`The number ${arr[i]} is a prime number`);
    }
  }
}

// Test the function
const testArray = [17, 4, 13, 20, 31];
checkForPrime(testArray);
```

The `isPrime` function works by iterating from 2 to the square root of the number in question. If it finds any integer that divides the number without leaving a remainder, it means the number is not prime. If the function completes the loop without finding any divisors, it returns `true` to indicate that the number is prime.

The `checkForPrime` function iterates through each element in the input array and checks it using the `isPrime` function. If the number is prime, it prints the number to the console.

